revision.text:
'''Kujuku Ōji''' (九十九王子) refers to a group of shrines along the {{ill|Kumano Kodō|ja|熊野古道|12=draft}} that were primarily organized between the 12th and 13th centuries by {{ill|Kumano Shugendō|ja|熊野修験|12=draft}}, serving as guides for imperial and aristocratic pilgrimages to {{ill|Kumano|ja|熊野|12=draft}}. These shrines were prayed to for the protection of pilgrims and are distributed along the {{ill|Kiiji|ja|紀伊路|12=draft}} and {{ill|Nakahechi|ja|中辺路|12=draft}} routes.

[[File:Daimonzaka17 1024.jpg|thumb|180px|Tafuji Ōji site ({{ill|Daimonzaka|ja|大門坂|fr|12=draft}})]]

== Overview ==

=== Emergence and Decline ===
The first documented mention of an Ōji is found in the pilgrimage record ''{{ill|Ihonushi (庵主)|ja|いほぬし|12=draft}}'', attributed to {{ill|Masuki|ja|増基|12=draft}}, which describes the "Ōji Cave" (わうじのいはや) at the site of {{ill|Hananoiwaya Shrine|ja|花窟神社|12=draft}}. This document is believed to have been written between the late 10th and mid-11th centuries. The next reference appears in {{ill|Dai Goki|ja|大御記|12=draft}}, a diary by {{ill|Fujiwara no Tamefusa|ja|藤原為房|12=draft}}, which records a {{ill|Hōbei|ja|奉幣|12=draft}} ritual at {{ill|Hine Ōji|ja|日根王子|12=draft}} in {{ill|1082|永保元年}}. By the 12th century, the number of Ōji shrines increased rapidly, reaching their peak between the 12th and 13th centuries. However, many of these new Ōji were short-lived. After the {{ill|Kamakura Period|ja|鎌倉時代|12=draft}}, changes in pilgrimage practices and a decline in Kumano pilgrimages led to their general decline.

=== What Are Ōji Shrines? ===
Ōji shrines were places where rituals were conducted during pilgrimages. Key rituals included hōbei and sutra chanting, often blending Buddhist and Shinto elements. Contrary to popular belief, no evidence suggests that these rituals included worshipping the {{ill|Kumano Sanzan|ja|熊野三山|12=draft}} from afar. The shrines were not used for resupplying goods, as their primary purpose was the protection of pilgrims. This belief stemmed from the recognition of Ōji as divine offspring of Kumano Gongen.

The organization of these shrines was carried out by Kumano Shugendō practitioners, who identified local deities along the pilgrimage routes and designated them as Ōji shrines. The term "Ōji" reflects the Shugendō belief that guardian deities often appear as childlike figures (童子).

=== Five Major Ōji Shrines ===
[[File:241006 Fujishiro-jinja Kainan Wakayama pref Japan30s3.jpg|thumb|Fujishiro Ōji]]
[[File:切目王子.jpg|thumb|Kirime Ōji]]
[[File:Takijiri-oji shrine 2.jpg|thumb|Takijiri Ōji]]
[[File:HOSSHINMON-oji.JPG|thumb|Hosshinmon Ōji]]

Among the Ōji shrines, five are considered particularly prestigious, referred to as the {{ill|Five Major Ōji|ja|五体王子|12=draft}}. These shrines are thought to enshrine deities known as the {{ill|Five Sons of Kumano|ja|五所王子|12=draft}} (若一王子, 禅師宮, 聖宮, 児宮, 子守宮). The five major Ōji include {{ill|Fujishiro Ōji|ja|藤代王子|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kirime Ōji|ja|切目王子|12=draft}}, {{ill|Inabane Ōji|ja|稲葉根王子|12=draft}}, {{ill|Takijiri Ōji|ja|滝尻王子|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Hosshinmon Ōji|ja|発心門王子|12=draft}}.

=== Ōji Shrines Along the Ōhechi ===
Several shrines along the {{ill|Ōhechi|ja|大辺路|12=draft}}, although bearing the name "Ōji," are not included in the Kujuku Ōji definition. These shrines are associated with {{ill|Tōzan-ha|ja|当山派|12=draft}}, a school of Shugendō, and were established after the {{ill|Nanboku-chō Period|ja|南北朝時代|12=draft}}. They lack connections to imperial pilgrimages and are not considered part of the Kujuku Ōji.

== List of Kujuku Ōji ==
[[File:Jonangu shrine.jpg|thumb|Jōnangū Shrine]]
[[File:八軒家船着場.JPG|thumb|Hakkenya Dock]]

The term "Kujuku Ōji" does not indicate precisely 99 shrines but rather symbolizes a large number.<ref name="豊島修 (1992)、52頁">{{Cite book|和書|author=豊島修|title=死の国・熊野|publisher=講談社|series=講談社現代新書|year=1992|isbn=4-06-149103-2}}</ref>

Below is a list of 101 shrines, including those that have been reconstructed or identified through historical records.

* {{ill|Jōnangū|ja|城南宮|12=draft}} – Starting point from Kyoto
* {{ill|Hakkenya Dock|ja|八軒家船着場|12=draft}} – Landing dock from Kyoto to Osaka
